I&#x27;m not sure I see how this changes much.  My point is that with laziness, your explosion doesn&#x27;t happen right where you unwrap a Maybe in the code.  It happens where you evaluate the unwrapping.<p>Apologies for the ninja edit above, but this scala seems to show it isn&#x27;t just IO that is at danger here.<p><pre><code>     class Foo(x : =>String) {
        def happy = println(&quot;I&#x27;m good.&quot;)
        lazy val ack = x
        def sad = println(ack)
     }
</code></pre>
Again, if I do &quot;new Foo(None.get)&quot;, I can call happy as much as I want, but &quot;sad&quot; will blow up.<p>Now, I do not and could not claim that this sort of nonsense would have proliferated with the same abandon as null.  I am claiming that this is not that unlike a null pointer exception, though.
